  "prompt": "What is the legal history of money laundering prohibitions?",
  "response": "The legal history of money laundering prohibitions developed gradually over several decades:\n\n1. Early Origins:\n- Emerged as a legal concept in the 1930s\n- Initially focused on preventing criminal organizations from concealing illegal profits\n\n2. Key Milestones:\n- 1970: Bank Secrecy Act (U.S.) first introduced comprehensive reporting requirements\n- 1980s: Significant expansion of anti-money laundering (AML) regulations\n- 1989: Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established internationally\n\n3. Major Legislative Developments:\n- 1986: Money Laundering Control Act (U.S.)\n- 1990: European Union's first anti-money laundering directive\n- 2001: USA PATRIOT Act substantially expanded legal frameworks\n\n4. International Cooperation:\n- United Nations conventions addressing transnational organized crime\n- Increased global standardization of AML regulations\n- Enhanced information sharing between financial institutions and law enforcement\n\n5. Modern Trends:\n- Expanding regulations to cover cryptocurrency\n- More sophisticated detection technologies\n- Stricter compliance requirements for financial institutions\n\nThe legal framework continues evolving to address emerging financial technologies and criminal strategies.",
